# Zero Ring — Connector Feasibility Report
## What can actually be added without a partnership (verified, not assumed)

This replaces guessing with what each platform's own docs/policy actually say, checked directly. Use the **Feasibility Tier** column to decide what your UI connector picker shows now vs. later.

---

## 1. Feasibility tiers (add this field to the registry schema in `01_CORE_ARCHITECTURE.md §3`)

| Tier | Meaning | Registry field |
|---|---|---|
| **A — Self-serve, no gatekeeper** | Public dev portal, OAuth or API key, instant approval | `feasibility: "self_serve"` |
| **B — Self-serve but rate/quota limited or premium-gated** | Works standalone but some features need the user's own paid plan on that service | `feasibility: "self_serve_limited"` |
| **C — Invite/waitlist program** | Exists, documented, but requires application and approval before you get credentials | `feasibility: "invite_gated"` |
| **D — Partnership/business-only** | No individual-developer path exists at all | `feasibility: "partnership_only"` |
| **E — No official API; accessibility-automation only** | You're not calling an API, you're operating the app's UI like a human — inherits Level 2's reliability ceiling and, for some apps, real ToS/ban risk | `feasibility: "accessibility_only"` |

Ship your connector picker UI **sorted by tier**, A/B first. Don't show D as "coming soon" — show it as "not available" so you're not promising something you can't deliver.

